\b\fs24 7. Current Security Limitations And Risks\b0\fs22\par
\par
This section documents what is currently missing or weak in the present implementation.\par
\par
\b 7.1 Authentication Is Currently Mock / Demo Style\b0\par
\par
The login flow currently:\par
\par
\tab\bullet\tab uses hardcoded sample users in the frontend\par
\tab\bullet\tab uses a shared demonstration password `password123`\par
\tab\bullet\tab stores login state in `localStorage`\par
\tab\bullet\tab does not validate credentials against the Laravel backend\par
\par
Current implication:\par
\par
\tab\bullet\tab authentication is not currently a strong security boundary\par
\par
\b 7.2 API Authorization Is Not Clearly Enforced\b0\par
\par
The reviewed API routes do not show visible authentication or role middleware for business endpoints.\par
\par
Current implication:\par
\par
\tab\bullet\tab backend access control is not clearly enforced at route level\par
\tab\bullet\tab UI role restrictions should not be treated as true security enforcement\par
\par
\b 7.3 Password Creation Requirements Are Not Enforced\b0\par
\par
Current-state password concerns:\par
\par
\tab\bullet\tab the mock login uses a weak shared sample password\par
\tab\bullet\tab the mock register page accepts any non-empty password\par
\tab\bullet\tab the operational new-user admin flow does not collect a password from the UI\par
\tab\bullet\tab the backend may generate a random password if one is omitted\par
\tab\bullet\tab no explicit policy was found for:\par
\tab\bullet\tab minimum length\par
\tab\bullet\tab complexity\par
\tab\bullet\tab rotation\par
\tab\bullet\tab history\par
\tab\bullet\tab breach checking\par
\tab\bullet\tab forced first-use change\par
\par
\b 7.4 No Proven MFA Implementation\b0\par
\par
Although the UI includes a two-factor toggle:\par
\par
\tab\bullet\tab no backend MFA challenge flow was identified\par
\tab\bullet\tab no enrollment, recovery, or enforcement workflow was found\par
\par
\b 7.5 No Explicit Sensitive Route Throttling Observed\b0\par
\par
The reviewed application code does not currently demonstrate explicit throttling on:\par
\par
\tab\bullet\tab login attempts\par
\tab\bullet\tab test notification actions\par
\tab\bullet\tab import actions\par
\tab\bullet\tab administrative changes\par
\par
\b 7.6 No Explicit Browser Security Header Hardening Observed\b0\par
\par
No custom implementation was found for:\par
\par
\tab\bullet\tab `Content-Security-Policy`\par
\tab\bullet\tab `X-Frame-Options` or equivalent framing restriction\par
\tab\bullet\tab `X-Content-Type-Options`\par
\tab\bullet\tab `Referrer-Policy`\par
\tab\bullet\tab `Strict-Transport-Security`\par
\par
\b 7.7 HTTPS Enforcement Not Evident In App Code\b0\par
\par
The reviewed code does not explicitly enforce HTTPS.\par
\par
Current implication:\par
\par
\tab\bullet\tab secure transport depends on external hosting / reverse proxy / web-server configuration\par
\par
\b 7.8 Contract File Upload Security Not Yet Implemented\b0\par
\par
The UI currently exposes a contract document upload interaction, but no fully implemented secure server-side upload flow was identified.\par
\par
Missing current controls include:\par
\par
\tab\bullet\tab server-side MIME validation\par
\tab\bullet\tab content scanning\par
\tab\bullet\tab private storage handling\par
\tab\bullet\tab access-controlled retrieval\par
\tab\bullet\tab upload audit trail\par
\par
\b 7.9 No Field-Level Encryption Of Business Data Observed\b0\par
\par
The reviewed app code does not currently show field-level encryption for:\par
\par
\tab\bullet\tab contract descriptions\par
\tab\bullet\tab counterparties\par
\tab\bullet\tab notification recipients\par
\tab\bullet\tab file references\par
\par
This means application-layer data protection is limited mainly to standard database persistence and framework capability rather than explicit data-at-rest encryption logic.\par
\par
\b 7.10 Notification Delivery Security Is Limited\b0\par
\par
The system currently tracks notification settings and logs, but the reviewed code does not demonstrate a complete hardened provider integration for real outbound:\par
\par
\tab\bullet\tab email\par
\tab\bullet\tab SMS\par
\tab\bullet\tab WhatsApp\par
\par
\b 7.11 Audit Log Protection Could Be Stronger\b0\par
\par
Audit logging exists, but the reviewed implementation does not show:\par
\par
\tab\bullet\tab immutable logging\par
\tab\bullet\tab tamper evidence\par
\tab\bullet\tab central SIEM forwarding\par
\tab\bullet\tab retention controls\par
\tab\bullet\tab alerting on high-risk events\par
\par
\b\fs24 8. Current Password Security Position\b0\fs22\par
\par
As of the reviewed implementation, the strongest password-related control currently present is:\par
\par
\tab\bullet\tab hashed password storage in Laravel for persisted backend users\par
\par
The system does not currently demonstrate enforced password policy for active application sign-in and user lifecycle.\par
\par
Therefore, the current system should be described as:\par
\par
\tab\bullet\tab having backend password hashing capability\par
\tab\bullet\tab not yet having mature password governance or password-authentication enforcement\par
\par
\b\fs24 9. Current Encryption Position\b0\fs22\par
\par
\b Currently Present\b0\par
\par
\tab\bullet\tab Laravel encryption capability using `AES-256-CBC`\par
\tab\bullet\tab hashed password storage\par
\tab\bullet\tab origin-restricted CORS\par
\par
\b Not Currently Evidenced In The Reviewed Code\b0\par
\par
\tab\bullet\tab field-level encryption for contract records\par
\tab\bullet\tab database encryption at rest logic in app layer\par
\tab\bullet\tab secure encrypted document storage workflow\par
\tab\bullet\tab explicit HSTS / TLS enforcement in application code\par
\par
\b\fs24 10. Current-State Security Posture Summary\b0\fs22\par
\par
The Strauss Daly Contract Management System currently has:\par
\par
\tab\bullet\tab reasonable business-data validation\par
\tab\bullet\tab useful audit visibility\par
\tab\bullet\tab some baseline secure coding practices from Laravel\par
\tab\bullet\tab password hashing for stored backend user credentials\par
\par
The system currently does not yet have:\par
\par
\tab\bullet\tab real production-grade authentication\par
\tab\bullet\tab confirmed backend authorization enforcement\par
\tab\bullet\tab MFA\par
\tab\bullet\tab strong password policy enforcement\par
\tab\bullet\tab hardened file upload controls\par
\tab\bullet\tab explicit browser security header hardening\par
\tab\bullet\tab explicit API abuse protection\par
\par
Current assessment:\par
\par
\tab\bullet\tab appropriate only for controlled internal development or restricted internal usage\par
\tab\bullet\tab not yet suitable for broader exposure without additional security hardening\par
\par
\b\fs24 11. Recommendations\b0\fs22\par
\par
The following recommendations are based on the current code state and should be treated as improvement actions, not current features.\par
\par
\b 11.1 Authentication And Authorization\b0\par
\par
Recommended:\par
\par
1. Replace mock login with real Laravel-backed authentication.\par
2. Implement Sanctum or a comparable session/token strategy.\par
3. Enforce authentication middleware on all business APIs.\par
4. Enforce backend RBAC for:\par
\tab\bullet\tab contract administration\par
\tab\bullet\tab user management\par
\tab\bullet\tab settings changes\par
\tab\bullet\tab notification configuration\par
\tab\bullet\tab audit visibility\par
\par
\b 11.2 Password Security\b0\par
\par
Recommended:\par
\par
1. Enforce a password policy:\par
\tab\bullet\tab minimum 12 characters\par
\tab\bullet\tab uppercase\par
\tab\bullet\tab lowercase\par
\tab\bullet\tab numeric\par
\tab\bullet\tab special character\par
2. Block common and breached passwords.\par
3. Require first-login password reset for new users.\par
4. Add secure password reset flow with expiring tokens.\par
5. Add account lockout / throttling for failed login attempts.\par
\par
\b 11.3 MFA\b0\par
\par
Recommended:\par
\par
1. Implement real MFA for privileged roles.\par
2. Add enrollment, recovery, enforcement, and audit trails for MFA.\par
\par
\b 11.4 Transport And Browser Security\b0\par
\par
Recommended:\par
\par
1. Enforce HTTPS in production.\par
2. Add HSTS.\par
3. Add:\par
\tab\bullet\tab CSP\par
\tab\bullet\tab X-Content-Type-Options\par
\tab\bullet\tab frame protection\par
\tab\bullet\tab Referrer-Policy\par
4. Ensure secure cookie settings if session authentication is introduced.\par
\par
\b 11.5 API Hardening\b0\par
\par
Recommended:\par
\par
1. Add throttling to:\par
\tab\bullet\tab login\par
\tab\bullet\tab import\par
\tab\bullet\tab notification test\par
\tab\bullet\tab user administration\par
\tab\bullet\tab settings changes\par
2. Add stricter production error handling to avoid leaking internal details.\par
3. Limit CORS strictly to approved production origins.\par
\par
\b 11.6 File Upload Security\b0\par
\par
Recommended:\par
\par
1. Implement backend upload processing.\par
2. Validate file type and size server-side.\par
3. Scan uploads for malware.\par
4. Store files outside the public web root.\par
5. Use controlled download endpoints or signed URLs.\par
6. Add upload/download/delete audit entries.\par
\par
\b 11.7 Monitoring And Audit Strengthening\b0\par
\par
Recommended:\par
\par
1. Forward logs to a central monitoring platform or SIEM.\par
2. Add alerting for privileged changes and suspicious actions.\par
3. Introduce retention and integrity controls for audit records.\par
\par
\b 11.8 Data Protection\b0\par
\par
Recommended:\par
\par
1. Evaluate encryption at rest for database and backups.\par
2. Consider field-level encryption for sensitive contract attributes where justified.\par
3. Protect outbound notification secrets in a secure secret-management process.\par
\par
